08062nam a22012615i 9783110216097DE-B159720211217065530.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||211217t20092009gw     fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)948656034  a97831102160977 a10.1515/97831102160972doi  a(DE-B1597)36133  a(OCoLC)851033502  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  agwcDE 4aP120.V37bD44 2009eb 7aLAN0090002bisacsh04a417/.222200aDescribing and Modeling Variation in Grammar /ced. by Jürg Fleischer, Andreas Dufter, Guido Seiler. 1aBerlin ;aBoston : bDe Gruyter Mouton, c[2009] 4c©2009  a1 online resource (410 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aTrends in Linguistics. Studies and Monographs [TiLSM] ,x1861-4302 ;v2040 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aWhile variation within individual languages has traditionally been focused upon in sociolinguistics, its relevance for grammatical theory has only recently been acknowledged. On the methodological side, there is an ongoing competition between large-scale statistical analyses and investigations that rely more heavily on introspection and elicited grammaticality judgements. The aim of this volume is to bridge the 'cultural gap' between empirical-variationist and formal-theoretical approaches in linguistics. The volume offers case studies that seek to combine corpus-based and competence-based approaches to the description of variation. In doing so, it opens up new avenues for locating and analyzing variability, both at the level of the individual speaker and between speakers of different dialects and generations. The contributions document the plurality of current research into models of grammatical competence that live up to the challenge of variationist data. More specifically, parameter-based (e.g. Minimalist), constraint-based (e.g. Optimality Theoretic), and usage-based (e.g. Construction Grammar) approaches to variation are discussed. The volume therefore is of interest to a broad public within linguistics, including syntacticians of different theoretical persuasion, morphologists and sociolinguists. While a majority of contributions addresses facets of variation in English and German, the volume also includes variationist studies written by specialists of French, Dutch, Icelandic, and Uralic.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 17. Dez 2021) 0aGrammar, Comparative and generalxVariation. 0aLanguage and languagesxVariation. 0aSociolinguistics. 4aMorphologie. 4aSoziolinguistik. 4aSprachvariation. 4aSyntax. 7aLANGUAGE ARTS & DISCIPLINES / Linguistics / General.2bisacsh  aMorphology.  alinguistic theories.  asociolinguistics.  asyntax.  avariation (language).1 aAbraham, Werner, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBerman, Judith, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCappelle, Bert, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChalcraft, Faye, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCornips, Leonie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDufter, Andreas, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDufter, Andreas, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aElsig, Martin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEythórsson, Thórhallur, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFleischer, Jürg, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFleischer, Jürg, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aHaser, Verena, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJónsson, Jóhannes Gísli, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relat